  "signature": "ed25519:b7d3e9f1a2c4e6f8b0d2e4f6a8c0e2f4b6d8f0a2c4e6f8b0d2e4f6a8c0e2f4b6",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) used under validated institutional license with documented version control and regression test suite. Required Gradation 2: documented QA plan and version-controlled analysis files.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 was used under an institutional site license with full regression testing against ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems. Analysis files were version-controlled in a Git repository with commit hashes recorded in the simulation log. QA plan is documented in the modeling SOP (Rev. 3)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verified against published analytical solutions for beam bending and contact problems representative of the pedicle screw geometry. Required Gradation 2: verification against at least one relevant benchmark.",
      "rationale": "The FEA code was verified against the Hertz contact analytical solution and a cantilever beam benchmark matching the screw shank aspect ratio. Results agreed within 0.8% for contact pressure and 1.1% for tip deflection, confirming correct implementation of the contact and structural elements used in the pedicle screw model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed on the construct model with at least three element sizes; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization error. Required Gradation 2: convergence demonstrated with GCI < 5% on primary QoI.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements) was performed. Richardson extrapolation yielded a Grid Convergence Index of 2.3% for construct stiffness and 3.1% for yield force. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence criteria documented and residuals monitored. Required Gradation 1: default solver tolerances applied and residuals recorded.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver was used with force residual tolerance of 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance of 1e-5. Convergence was achieved in all load steps across all 11 simulation cases. No divergence or unconverged load steps were observed. Residual histories are archived in the simulation log."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup, boundary conditions, and loading by a second qualified analyst. Required Gradation 2: documented peer review of simulation inputs and outputs.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior FEA analyst (not involved in model construction) reviewed the boundary condition definitions, material assignments, contact pair definitions, and load application against the ASTM F1717 test standard. All discrepancies identified during review were resolved prior to production runs. Review sign-off is documented in the project record."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification of constitutive model selection for titanium alloy screw and UHMWPE block. Required Gradation 2: documented justification with literature support for model form choices.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model was selected for the Ti-6Al-4V screw based on published tensile test data (ASTM E8) and prior FDA validation studies. Linear elasticity was applied to the UHMWPE test block, consistent with the small deformation regime observed in the compression-bending test. Model form choices are documented with supporting literature references in the modeling report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs sourced from traceable measurements or certified material datasheets. Required Gradation 2: inputs traceable to measurements with documented uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus and yield strength for Ti-6Al-4V were sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon tests (mean E = 114 GPa, σ_y = 895 MPa) with documented measurement uncertainty. Screw geometry was derived from calibrated CMM measurements of production screws. Input uncertainty distributions (normal for material properties, uniform for geometric tolerances) were propagated through the model ensemble using Monte Carlo sampling (n=500 draws), with results summarized in the UQ report. A screening sensitivity study performed during model development identified thread pitch and root radius as the most influential geometric parameters; full characterization of input driver rankings is captured in the UQ documentation package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation test specimens are production-representative devices from the same manufacturing lot. Required Gradation 2: specimens from production lot with documented traceability.",
      "rationale": "All N=11 test constructs used production non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws from a single manufacturing lot (Lot 2021-NC-7500), with full dimensional inspection records. Specimen traceability is documented in the test report (TR-2021-F1717-NC)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation testing conducted under at least two distinct test conditions (e.g., varying load rates or fixation configurations) to assess condition sensitivity. Required Gradation 2: testing across multiple conditions.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 conditions (5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature, standard UHMWPE block). Only one test condition was evaluated, achieving Gradation 1. This factor is below the required level; the gap is acknowledged and accepted given the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol and the absence of clinical evidence suggesting rate-dependent failure in the COU loading regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test configuration inputs. Required Gradation 2: documented parameter-by-parameter equivalency mapping.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each FEA input (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) to the corresponding measured or specified test parameter. Differences exceeding 1% were flagged; none were identified. The equivalency table is included as Appendix B of the validation report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of FEA QoIs against experimental data using a pre-established metric (E/uval < 1.96 and relative error < 10%). Required Gradation 2: quantitative comparison with pre-established acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared: construct stiffness (E/uval = 1.41, 6.2% error), yield force (E/uval = 1.68, 8.7% error), and force at 40 mm (E/uval = 0.93, 5.1% error). All three QoIs satisfy both pre-established acceptance criteria. Comparison methodology follows ASME V&V 40 Section 6.4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation are directly relevant to the clinical failure modes and COU decision. Required Gradation 2: documented linkage between QoIs and clinical risk.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the clinical risk of screw fatigue fracture and construct loosening under physiological loading. The linkage is documented in the risk-to-QoI traceability matrix (Appendix A of the validation report)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are conducted under conditions sufficiently similar to the COU to support extrapolation of credibility. Required Gradation 2: documented similarity argument between validation and COU conditions.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending of a non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct) closely matches the COU (FEA-based design substantiation for the same device class and loading mode). The similarity argument is documented in Section 3 of the validation plan, noting that dynamic and fatigue loading are outside the current COU scope."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors were assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved the required gradation level. The single below-requirement factor (Test conditions, Gradation 1 vs. required Gradation 2) was accepted given the standardized ASTM F1717 protocol and the absence of evidence for rate-dependent failure in the clinical use regime. All three QoIs satisfy pre-established quantitative acceptance criteria (E/uval < 1.96 and relative error < 10%). Uncertainty quantification was performed across material and geometric input distributions; results confirm that model predictions are robust to input variability within the ranges observed in production. The overall credibility package is judged sufficient to support the Medium assurance level required for a Class II device at model risk level 3.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
